  "observation": "Brainstorm triggered by plateau. 4 proposals generated.",
  "suggestion": "The plateau indicates convergence to a small set of equivalent local optima under the current fitness function. All viable strategies pull toward the same attractor because there is no distinction between them once basic survival threshold is met. Breakthrough requires either (1) orthogonal payoff dimensions (cooperation, trade), (2) non-stationary targets (temporal cycles), or (3) irreversible choices that create distinct niches. The system has saturated the available strategy space — adding new dimensions is mandatory.; [medium] Symbiotic resource exchange system — allow organisms to donate/receive resources (lipids, photosynthetic energy) from nearby neighbors. Add new action type: TRANSFER(resource_type, target_id, amount). Score transfers that increase both donor and recipient fitness (mutual gain) differently than competitive behaviors. — Current fitness is purely competitive. Introducing cooperation creates a new payoff surface orthogonal to survival competition. Organisms can specialize and trade instead of converging to generalists. This multiplies effective strategy space without changing simulation physics.; [medium] Temporal environmental cycles — add 3-phase world: growth phase (high energy availability, reward reproduction), scarcity phase (low resources, reward efficiency), beauty phase (external criteria shift to favor specific morphologies or colors). Each phase lasts ~50 cycles. Organisms must trade off specialization vs. phenotypic flexibility. — Plateau suggests organisms have found stable local optima. Moving targets force continuous adaptation. The fitness function becomes time-dependent, breaking the static attractor. Organisms that can adjust strategy between phases will outcompete single-strategy variants.; [hard] Developmental branching with irreversible commitment — at age 10, each organism chooses a developmental path (mobility-focused, photosynthetic capacity, defense structure) that constrains further growth. Each path opens 2-3 new cell type options but closes others. Fitness payoff depends on path-specific optimization in the chosen niche. — Current morphologies likely converge because organisms can always 'try everything.' Forcing early specialization commitment increases the effective morphospace (path × strategy combinations) and creates frequency-dependent selection: early-movers in a niche prosper, but once saturated, minority paths become advantageous. Breaks symmetry.",
